{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501832"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:34:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:34:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1794"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1794","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1794"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.47,0.16,0.02,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1794"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112949"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1794","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1794"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1794"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94981"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"181"},{"type":"tags","id":"402"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4032"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3506"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3740"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8851"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28381"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42406"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43105"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43852"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112949"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a five-month history of progressively worsening ankle oedema. He also reports exertional dyspnoea, palpitations and chest pressure when exerting himself.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a medical history of type 2 diabetes and hypertension. He has never smoked but drinks one bottle of wine daily. His medications include metformin and perindopril.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears stable with vital signs within normal limits. There is marked bilateral pitting ankle oedema. His heart sounds are dual with no murmurs and regular rhythm. Chest auscultation reveals bibasilar crepitations. His abdomen is soft and non-tender with no distension or masses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPotassium 6.0 mmol/L (3.5-4.9)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUrea 11 mmol/L (2.7-8.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECreatinine 155 \u03bcmol/L (50-120)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGlucose 12 mmol/L (3.2-5.5) fasting\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAlbumin 26 g/L (36-46)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ELiver enzymes mildly elevated\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUrine albumin/creatinine ratio 5.6 (\u0026lt;2.5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations would be most appropriate in determining the underlying cause of his peripheral oedema?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["B-type natriuretic peptide (BNP)","Echocardiography","Liver ultrasound","ECG","24-hour urine protein"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s peripheral oedema has multiple possible aetiologies, including heart failure, renal failure and cirrhosis. In particular renal failure is unlikely to cause such dyspnoea except in advanced renal disease (e.g. stage IV or V) or in the absence of an additional fluid load (e.g intravenous fluids). Therefore congestive heart failure is most likely based on the combination of respiratory fluid overload as well as peripheral oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore an \u003Cstrong\u003Eechocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E would be most appropriate in determining the underlying aetiology and severity of the disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003EECG\u003C/strong\u003E is a mainstay of assessment of any patient with shortness of breath, palpitations or chest pain, however, while arrhythmia may be a cause of cardiac failure, it is unlikely in this case to determine the underlying aetiology given that this patient\u0027s pulse was regular. Furthermore, in this case the exertional palpitations are more likely to be secondary to heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESevere hypoalbuminaemia may contribute to oedema in context of liver cirrhosis or nephrotic syndrome, however given these disorders are less likely to induce pulmonary oedema than heart failure, a \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003E24-urine protein\u003C/strong\u003E are not likely to determine the cause in this case. The albumin creatinine ratio of 5.6 is relatively mild and is a common finding in hypertension or diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003EB-type natriuretic peptide (BNP)\u003C/strong\u003E is a useful biomarker for diagnosing heart failure and can help rule out heart failure when levels are normal, it does not provide information about cardiac structure, function, or the specific cause of heart failure. BNP may be elevated in various conditions including renal failure, which this patient has evidence of. An echocardiogram provides more comprehensive information about cardiac function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECauses of acute bilateral peripheral oedema include medication side effects (calcium channel blockers), or bilateral DVT. While other chronic causes of bilateral oedema include lymphoedema or myxoedema - although neither are true oedematous states.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Common causes of bilateral ankle oedema include heart failure, cirrhosis, renal failure and chronic venous insufficiency.","Echocardiography is the investigation of choice for suspected heart failure.","The combination of peripheral oedema with exertional dyspnoea and bibasilar crepitations strongly suggests heart failure."],"references":["Goyal A, Cusick AS, Bhutta BS. Peripheral Edema. [Updated 2023 Aug 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554452/","Marwick TH. The role of echocardiography in heart failure. J Nucl Med. 2015 Jun;56 Suppl 4:31S-38S. doi: 10.2967/jnumed.114.150433. PMID: 26033901.\n Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26033901/","Shah AM, Cikes M, Prasad N, Li G, Getchevski S, Claggett B, Rizkala A, Lukashevich I, O\u0027Meara E, Ryan JJ, Shah SJ, Mullens W, Zile MR, Lam CSP, McMurray JJV, Solomon SD; PARAGON-HF Investigators. Echocardiographic Features of Patients With Heart Failure and Preserved Left Ventricular Ejection Fraction. J Am Coll Cardiol. 2019 Dec 10;74(23):2858-2873. doi: 10.1016/j.jacc.2019.09.063. PMID: 31806129. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31806129/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94981"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1794"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94981"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-08T16:29:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-08T16:29:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1794"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112949"}